    idealAnswer: `Introduction: Land reforms were a central pillar of post-independence agrarian policy in India, aimed at restructuring exploitative colonial-era land relations and promoting equity and productivity in agriculture.

Main Features: The first major component was the abolition of intermediary tenures such as the Zamindari, Jagirdari and Mahalwari systems, transferring land rights directly to actual cultivators and eliminating exploitative rent-collecting intermediaries. Tenancy reforms sought to provide security of tenure to tenant cultivators and regulate rents to prevent exploitation by landlords. Land ceiling legislation was introduced to impose an upper limit on individual landholding size, with surplus land meant to be redistributed to landless and marginal farmers, though implementation was often undermined through benami transfers and legal loopholes. Consolidation of fragmented landholdings was undertaken to improve agricultural efficiency, and cooperative farming was promoted, though with limited success, as an alternative to both large private estates and fragmented small holdings.

Assessment: Implementation of these reforms varied significantly across states, being relatively more successful in states like Kerala and West Bengal, which saw stronger political will and mobilization, but weaker elsewhere due to landlord resistance, bureaucratic delay, and legal loopholes, resulting in the emergence of a stronger middle peasantry rather than complete elimination of agrarian inequality.

Conclusion: Land reforms thus significantly altered India's agrarian structure by curbing the power of large intermediaries, even though their uneven and incomplete implementation left substantial rural land inequality unresolved.`,
