    idealAnswer: `Introduction: The New Education Policy (NEP) 2020 represents a comprehensive overhaul of India's education framework, replacing the policy of 1986, aiming to transform both school and higher education systems.

Salient Features: NEP 2020 restructures school education into a new 5+3+3+4 pedagogical framework covering foundational, preparatory, middle and secondary stages, replacing the earlier 10+2 structure, with strong emphasis on achieving foundational literacy and numeracy by early grades. It promotes multilingualism, recommending instruction in the mother tongue or regional language at least until grade five, and encourages flexibility in subject choice, blurring rigid boundaries between arts, science and vocational streams. In higher education, it introduces multiple entry and exit options with an Academic Bank of Credits, a four-year undergraduate programme with research options, and proposes a single overarching regulatory body, the Higher Education Commission of India, to streamline governance. The policy emphasizes reducing rote learning in favour of critical thinking, experiential learning and holistic, multidisciplinary education, and mandates the integration of vocational education starting from early schooling to bridge the gap between education and employability.

Conclusion: NEP 2020 thus envisions a flexible, multidisciplinary and skills-oriented education system, though its full sociological impact depends on effective implementation across India's diverse and unevenly resourced educational institutions.`,
